### Namespaces

Namespaces are used to organize code into logical groups and prevent name collisions in large projects.

---

### Defining a Namespace

```cpp
namespace Math {
  const double PI = 3.14159;

  int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
  }

  class Calculator {
  public:
    int multiply(int a, int b) { return a * b; }
  };
}
```

---

### Accessing Namespace Members

```cpp
// Qualified name
cout << Math::PI;
int sum = Math::add(5, 3);
Math::Calculator calc;

// Using declaration
using Math::PI;
cout << PI;  // No need for Math::

// Using directive
using namespace Math;
cout << add(1, 2);  // All Math members available
```

---

### Nested Namespaces

```cpp
namespace Outer {
  namespace Inner {
    int value = 42;
  }
}

// C++17: nested namespace definition
namespace Outer::Inner {
  int another = 100;
}

cout << Outer::Inner::value;  // 42
```

---

### Inline Namespaces (C++11)

```cpp
namespace Library {
  inline namespace V2 {
    void func() { cout << "v2"; }
  }
  namespace V1 {
    void func() { cout << "v1"; }
  }
}

Library::func();  // Calls V2::func (inline makes it default)
```

---

### Anonymous Namespaces

```cpp
namespace {
  int internalVar = 10;  // Internal linkage (like static)
  void helper() { /* ... */ }
}
```

---

> **Key Point:** Avoid `using namespace std;` in header files. Use `using` declarations (`using std::cout;`) or fully qualified names for better clarity and to prevent pollution.

codeExample:
#include <iostream>

namespace Geometry {
  const double PI = 3.14159;

  double circleArea(double radius) {
    return PI * radius * radius;
  }
}

int main() {
  std::cout << "Area: " << Geometry::circleArea(5.0) << std::endl;
  return 0;
}
